cs.LO, cs.CG, cs.PL, cs.DS, cs.SC. 

The paper deals with a geometric statement and uses interactive realizability, a realizability semantics for classical logic, to extract a monotonic learning algorithm. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The paper also involves the real plane and convex hulls, which suggests it could belong to cs.CG (Computational Geometry). Additionally, the paper deals with real numbers and Cauchy sequences, which could place it in cs.PL (Programming Languages) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper discusses the behavior of the algorithm, which could relate to cs.SC (Symbolic Computation).
